segment.source: /Auto {CleanDataOnlyUpgrade}

segment.source: Performs an automated upgrade to Windows 10 or Windows 8.1 volume license editions only.
segment.target: Performs an automated upgrade to Windows 10 or Windows 8.1 volume license editions only.

segment.source: When /auto is used, an unattend file cannot be used.

segment.source: When /auto is used, Windows Setup consumes ei.cfg, an checks compatibility issues before starting the installation.

segment.source: If ei.cfg is malformed, setup exits silently and logs an exit code.

segment.source: Clean: Performs an clean install of Windows.
segment.target: Clean: Performs an clean install of Windows.

segment.source: DataOnly: Performs an upgrade of Windows, saving only data (and not apps.) If the data-only installation option is not available due to compatibility checks, Windows Setup will exit silently and log an exit code.
segment.target: DataOnly: Performs an upgrade of Windows, saving only data (and not apps.) If the data-only installation option is not available due to compatibility checks, Windows Setup will exit silently and log an exit code.

segment.source: Upgrade: Performs an upgrade of Windows saving apps and data.
segment.target: Upgrade: Performs an upgrade of Windows saving apps and data.

segment.source: If the upgrade installation option is not available, or the user needs to resolve an app compatibility issue, Windows Setup will exit silently and log an exit code.
segment.target: If the upgrade installation option is not available, or the user needs to resolve an app compatibility issue, Windows Setup will exit silently and log an exit code.

segment.source: /EMSPort: {COM1COM2 | | off} [/emsbaudrate:baudrate]
segment.target: /EMSPort: {COM1COM2 | | off} [/emsbaudrate:baudrate]

segment.source: Enables or disables Emergency Management Services (EMS) during Windows Setup and after the server operating system has been installed.
segment.target: Enables or disables Emergency Management Services (EMS) during Windows Setup and after the server operating system has been installed.

segment.source: The following arguments are used to specify the behavior of EMS during Windows Setup.
segment.target: The following arguments are used to specify the behavior of EMS during Windows Setup.

segment.source: COM1 enables EMS over COM1.
segment.target: COM1 enables EMS over COM1.

segment.source: Supported for x86 systems only.
segment.target: Supported for x86 systems only.

segment.source: COM2 enables EMS over COM2.
segment.target: COM2 enables EMS over COM2.

segment.source: Supported for x86 systems only.
segment.target: Supported for x86 systems only.

segment.source: usebiossettings uses the setting that the BIOS specifies.
segment.target: usebiossettings uses the setting that the BIOS specifies.

segment.source: For x86 systems, Windows uses the value from the Serial Port Console Redirection (SPCR) table.
segment.target: For x86 systems, Windows uses the value from the Serial Port Console Redirection (SPCR) table.

segment.source: If no SPCR table or EFI console device path is specified in the BIOS, Windows disables usebiossettings.usebiossettings
segment.target: If no SPCR table or EFI console device path is specified in the BIOS, Windows disables usebiossettings.usebiossettings

segment.source: off disables EMS.
segment.target: off disables EMS.

segment.source: If EMS is disabled in Windows Setup, you can later enable EMS by modifying the boot settings.
segment.target: If EMS is disabled in Windows Setup, you can later enable EMS by modifying the boot settings.
